### 🔹 `next()` — What it does:

The `next()` method in Java’s `Scanner` **returns the next token** (word/part of input)
**based on the delimiter**.

---

### 🧠 By default:

* Scanner splits input **by whitespace** (space, tab, newline).
* So calling `next()` returns the next **word**, not the whole line.

---

### ✅ In your example:

```java
String email = "name@email.com";
String username = new Scanner(email).useDelimiter("@").next();
System.out.println(username); // prints: name
```

* You **changed the delimiter** from default whitespace to `"@"`.
* So `Scanner` splits `"name@email.com"` into:
  `["name", "email.com"]`
* Then `next()` returns the **first token** = `"name"`

---

### ⚠️ Important:

* `next()` only gives **one token** — not all parts.
* If you call `next()` again, it gives `"email.com"` (the next token).
* If you keep calling `next()` after tokens are exhausted, you'll get a `NoSuchElementException`.

---

### 🔁 Compared to:

| Method       | Returns                       | Default Delimiter |
| ------------ | ----------------------------- | ----------------- |
| `next()`     | Next token (as `String`)      | Whitespace        |
| `nextLine()` | The **entire remaining line** | `\n` (newline)    |
| `nextInt()`  | Next token parsed as `int`    | Whitespace        |

